I"ü<p>Here‚Äôs a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_wild-ass_guess" target="_blank">SWAG</a>:. Over the past 6.5 years I‚Äôve conducted over 2 interviews per week tallying over 650 in total. I performed over 15 in a single week running the Duo Engineering internship program.</p>

<p>The compendium includes systems design sessions, algorithmic coding assessments, and introductory phone interviews. Behavioral interviews were the most prevalent.</p>

<p>Behavorial interviewing posits that <em>past behavior is the best predictor of future success</em>. Behavioral interview questions often come in the form ‚ÄúTell me about a time when‚Ä¶‚Äù or ‚ÄúHave you ever‚Ä¶?‚Äù</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Tell me about a time you provided critical feedback to a boss or superior?</p>
</blockquote>

<p>I‚Äôm not as interested in what you‚Äôd do in a hypothetical situation. Instead, I want you to show me what you have done in reality.</p>

<p>There are weaknesses of course.</p>

<p>Less tenured candidates may not have experienced different scenarios. An entry-level candidate may never have provided critical feedback to a superior.</p>

<p>A poor interviewee may get filtered out by a poor interviewer. Someone who doesn‚Äôt continue to probe and ask questions to draw the candidate out.</p>

<p>I‚Äôve seen workplace behaviors from hires repeatedly prove the value of behavioral interviews.</p>

<p>It makes me sad when I see candidates overthink behavioral interview questions. I‚Äôm not looking for <em>one</em> right answer; there are many. But I‚Äôm not trying to entrap the candidate. I want to hire great people. And I want them to do well in their interviews.</p>

<p>Below are 3 principles to follow to turn the corner in your interviews.</p>

<h2 id="tell-a-story">Tell a Story</h2>

<p>Really. Don‚Äôt tell me what you would do (more on that later).</p>

<p>If you can‚Äôt think of a story immediately, ask for a moment to collect your thoughts. I‚Äôd rather have you sit for 20 seconds in silence. Provide a meaningful anecdote rather than tell me that‚Äôs never happened to you.</p>

<p>If you can‚Äôt think of a story that‚Äôs an exact match, tell something that‚Äôs proximate. Tell me, ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know if this will be an exact match but I think it will help you understand a similar scenario.‚Äù</p>

<p>Telling stories involves details.</p>

<p>Yes, you could study and follow the STAR model. Treat me like a human.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>We were working on this project‚Ä¶
This was my role and who else was involved‚Ä¶
Here was the problem‚Ä¶
Here‚Äôs what I did and how others were involved‚Ä¶
